Name: McGovern, James P.
text:
Earlier this year, I nominated Dan Turton for the McCormack Award of Excellence, which honors longtime employees of the House of Representatives who have distinguished themselves through a career in public service.
¬†
Dan and I actually worked together as Congressional staffers. He tragically passed away earlier this year due to complications from Type 1 diabetes, leaving behind an incredible legacy and an amazing family. His wife Bree and his children, parents, and brothers all joined us yesterday at a ceremony in the Capitol Building acknowledging his lifetime of work on behalf of the American people by officially honoring him with the McCormack Award.
¬†
I was grateful to speak about the kind of person Dan was. He embodied what it means to be a public servant‚Äîworking tirelessly, humbly, across the aisle, and always for the good of the country. I was also able to recognize this year‚Äôs other awardee, Ted Daniel, an amazing leader in his own right who has spent 44 years keeping Congress running‚Äîwelcoming visitors, maintaining protocol, and upholding the safety and spirit of the institution.
¬†
Thank you to all who came out yesterday to honor these two incredible public servants.

Name: Johnson, Mike
text:
My statement on House passage of the FY25 NDAA: 

Today‚Äôs passage of the annual National Defense Authorization Act (NDAA) includes important wins for our troops and ensures our military has the necessary resources and support to defend our great nation.¬†Our men and women in uniform should know their first obligation is protecting our nation, not woke ideology. It‚Äôs disappointing to see 124 of my Democrat colleagues vote against our brave men and women in uniform over policies that have nothing to do with their intended mission.
¬†
That is why this year‚Äôs NDAA refocuses our military on its core mission of defending America. The legislation supports law enforcement operations and the deployment of the National Guard to the southwest border, expedites innovation and reduces the acquisition timeline for new weaponry, supports our allies, and strengthens our nuclear posture and missile defense programs.
¬†
Because we believe in peace through strength, we blocked the Biden Administration's plan to reduce the number of US special forces. We remain determined to confront increasingly hostile threats from Communist China, Russia, and Iran, and this legislation provides our military with the tools they need to deter our enemies and keep America safe.
¬†
We also believe it‚Äôs important to refocus the Pentagon on military lethality, not radical woke ideology. This legislation permanently bans transgender treatment for minors, prohibits critical race theory in military academies, ends the DEI bureaucracy, and combats antisemitism.
¬†
This legislation also reinforces our commitment to America‚Äôs brave men and women in uniform, and their families, by making landmark investments in their quality of life. I‚Äôm proud that we‚Äôre providing significant pay increases to our servicemembers, reducing barriers to employment for military spouses, and improving military housing and access to childcare.
¬†

Name: Collins, Mike
text:
On #ThisDayInHistory in 1953, Maj. Chuck Yeager set a speed record by flying the Bell X-1A to Mach 2.44 (about 1,650 mph) at Edwards Air Force Base, California. 

At 80,000 feet and Mach 2.4, the aircraft went into an uncontrollable spin on all three axes, dropping 51,000 feet in 51 seconds. Yeager's head struck the canopy, cracking it, and the control stick bent, but he eventually regained control at 25,000 feet and landed safely.

The speed record held for three years. Flight data, including Mach number, altitude, and G-forces, were recorded, showing significant fluctuations due to the violent tumble. During the spin, Yeager experienced up to 8 Gs, making him feel as if he weighed 1,600 pounds.

Name: Collins, Mike
text:
On #ThisDayInHistory in 2003, Saddam Hussein, the former dictator of Iraq, was captured after nine months of evasion following the U.S.-led invasion of Iraq.

Hussein had ruled Iraq for over two decades, using brutal tactics to maintain power, including chemical attacks on civilians and an eight-year war with Iran. His regime collapsed after the invasion, but Saddam went into hiding, leading to an extensive manhunt by U.S. forces.

The capture, codenamed "Red Dawn," was the result of months of intelligence gathering and strategic interrogations. U.S. Army interrogator Eric Maddox played a pivotal role, relying on empathy to build trust with detainees, leading him to key informants who helped pinpoint Saddam's location. The operation was executed by a large military force but succeeded without firing a shot. Saddam was found hiding in a small hole near his hometown of Tikrit, disheveled but resigned to his fate.

Name: Davis, Donald G.
text:
Friday in the First

Regina Griffin Smith, a lifelong resident of Martin County, NC, has made a profound impact on her community, especially for individuals with special needs. As an Autism Support Professional with the Autism Society NC, Regina‚Äôs advocacy stems from her personal experience as a mother to a daughter with autism. She works tirelessly to ensure families receive the resources and support they need.

Regina also serves as the Local Coordinator for Special Olympics NC, organizing events that promote inclusion and joy. She founded Grand Giving, an initiative that brings holiday gifts to nursing home residents, and has helped organize fundraisers for local causes.

Her efforts were instrumental in the creation of a playground in Williamston, NC, designed to cater to children with special needs. Regina‚Äôs work continues to inspire compassion, understanding, and acceptance, leaving a lasting impact on her community, particularly during Disabilities Awareness Month.

#FridaySpotlight

Name: Fitzpatrick, Brian K.
text:
Each week, we celebrate the remarkable stories of Hometown Heroes from across our district, individuals who rise up to inspire others. Today, we shine a spotlight on a truly extraordinary couple who have demonstrated resilience, strength, and unwavering hope in the face of unimaginable adversity‚Äîmeet this week's Hometown Heroes, Tony and Katie Ferrandino of Newtown.
 
For the Ferrandinos, life once seemed picture-perfect. Their son, Drew, was a vibrant child who filled their days with laughter and love. But on Drew‚Äôs third birthday, their world was forever changed when Drew experienced his first seizure. Over the next two years, they traveled across the country, sought out specialists, and refused to rest until they understood what was happening. At the age of five, Drew was diagnosed with Batten Disease (CLN2), a rare and devastating degenerative neurological condition‚Äîa disease for which there is no cure and is always fatal. For children like Drew, life expectancy is heartbreakingly short, with the disease robbing them of their ability to walk, talk, and even feed themselves. Yet, through it all, Drew‚Äôs spirit remained a beacon of light for his family.
 
Tragically, Drew passed away at just 12 years old on September 30, 2014. In the wake of such an indescribable loss, many would understandably be consumed by grief, but Drew and Katie Ferrandino chose a different path. Instead, they founded Drew‚Äôs Hope Research Foundation, dedicating their lives to funding research, advocating for new treatments, supporting other families, and spreading awareness about Batten Disease. What began as an act of love for their son has become a lifeline for countless families facing similar battles. Through Drew‚Äôs Hope, the Ferrandinos have supported over a dozen groundbreaking projects, including advancements in newborn screening, enzyme replacement therapies, and pioneering gene therapy. Each effort represents a step closer to a cure and a chance for children to have the futures they deserve.
 
The Ferrandinos exemplify what it means to rise above unimaginable hardship and channel grief into a force for good. Their work has not only propelled critical research but offered hope and support to countless families, ensuring no one faces this journey alone.

Name: Fitzpatrick, Brian K.
text:
Today, we celebrate the 388th anniversary of the @USNationalGuard, the oldest military organization in America. Born from the citizen militias of the Massachusetts Bay Colony, the National Guard has been an integral part of every chapter of American history‚Äîfrom the battlefields of the Revolutionary War and the beaches of Normandy to disaster relief efforts at home and peacekeeping missions abroad. The National Guard has always been ready and has always been there.

To the men and women of the National Guard, both past and present, we extend our gratitude for your courage, resilience, and selflessness. You embody the highest ideals of service and represent the very heart of America.

Happy 388th birthday to the U.S. National Guard!

Name: Collins, Mike
text:
On #ThisDayInHistory in 1799, George Washington, the first president of the United States and a key figure in the American Revolution, died at age 67 on his estate in Mount Vernon, Virginia.

Born in 1732 in Virginia, Washington began his military career in the Virginia militia during the French and Indian War. After the war, he returned to civilian life as a planter and a member of the Virginia House of Burgesses, where he became an outspoken critic of British policies toward the colonies. He was elected to the Continental Congress in 1774, and was appointed commander-in-chief of the Continental Army during the Revolutionary War. Washington led the American forces to victory, culminating in the British surrender at Yorktown in 1781.

After the war, Washington retired to Mount Vernon but returned to public service to preside over the Constitutional Convention. The following year, he was unanimously elected the first president of the United States. He served two terms, stepping down in 1797 to retire once again.

After Washington‚Äôs death, Henry Lee famously eulogized him as ‚ÄúFirst in war, first in peace, and first in the hearts of his countrymen.‚Äù

Name: Ernst, Joni
text:
üßµüêíHappy National Monkey Day!

While this day comes just once a year, Washington has been monkeying around with our tax dollars for way too long.

Here are 10 bananas examples that must be peeled back by @DOGE.üëá https://t.co/yTylP8C0bF

Name: Ernst, Joni
text:
A primate example of waste is when @NIH spent more than $7 million studying the effects of THC edibles on pregnant monkeys.

If you thought these stoners were bad, just wait until you hear about the junkie monkeys.

Name: Ernst, Joni
text:
For more than 30 years, @NIH has paid Wake Forest University $50 million to get monkeys addicted to nicotine, cocaine, and alcohol!

Talk about a barrel of monkeys.

Name: Ernst, Joni
text:
While some got hooked on drugs, alcohol, and gambling, @NIH wasted nearly $1 million putting monkeys on treadmills and studying their eye movement.

Researchers noted the monkey marathoners didn't see the ape-peal in running.

Name: Ernst, Joni
text:
It is said that lady luck is cruel, but not as cruel as the @NIH.

The agency spent $3.6 million getting monkeys addicted to cocaine and then forced them to gamble to get access to water.

Name: Ernst, Joni
text:
While you might be thinking enough of this monkey business, we are just getting started.

@NIH spent more than $5 million to record and simulate primates saying "will you marry me" in English.

Name: Ernst, Joni
text:
You can't put a price tag on love, and @NSF found that out the hard way.

It spent nearly $200,000 to study the history of same-sex sexual behavior in monkeys.

Name: Ernst, Joni
text:
With millions in tax dollars to spend, @NIH tried to put the theory of "monkey see, monkey do" to the test.

It spent $3.5 million to force baby monkeys to be cross-eyed and test their vision. üôà

Name: Ernst, Joni
text:
Love wasn't just in the air at @NSF, @NIH spent $230,000 to see if female monkeys were more interested in the male monkeys wearing red or green.

Turns out red truly is the color of love!‚ù§Ô∏è

Name: Ernst, Joni
text:
Getting monkeys hooked on drugs in America was clearly too boring, so @NIH went ape abroad.

It paid Chinese labs to conduct experimental drug tests on monkeys.

Name: Ernst, Joni
text:
Finally, we get to Dr. Fauci's funky monkey island.

Since 1979, Dr. Fauci‚Äôs @NIH division has maintained an island that currently houses 3,379 monkeys for use in taxpayer-funded experiments.

Managing the island has cost more than $66 million to date (adjusted for inflation).

Name: Ernst, Joni
text:
When it comes to these ridiculous and costly studies, the federal government needs to say, "not my circus, not my monkeys."

But if they won't, then I will work with @DOGE to put a stop to this monkey business. 

#MakeEmSqueal

Name: Fitzpatrick, Brian K.
text:
Each year, participating in the Wreaths Across America ceremonies is a deeply moving experience. Today, at Washington Crossing National Cemetery, we stood among the final resting places of today‚Äôs American heroes, who served our nation with courage and sacrifice, and at @WashXingPark, we laid wreaths upon the graves of Revolutionary War soldiers, whose resolve and sacrifice gave birth to the very ideals that define our nation. 
 
This year‚Äôs WAA theme, Live with Purpose, challenges us to reflect on the legacy of those who have served and currently serve our nation. Their purpose was clear: to defend this great country, often at tremendous personal cost. They answered the call of duty with courage, driven by a love of country and belief in the timeless principles of liberty and justice. To truly live with purpose is to honor their legacy by carrying their torch forward‚Äîto serve our communities with integrity, to support one another in times of need, and to teach future generations the sacred truth that freedom is both precious and fragile.
 
I extend my heartfelt gratitude to every volunteer and organizer who made these ceremonies possible. Your dedication ensures our nation's heroes are never forgotten and their legacies continue to inspire us to live with purpose and serve our communities.

text:
America‚Äôs farmers are struggling with record-high inflation, sinking crop prices, and burdensome regulations that threaten their livelihoods and ultimately our ability to sustain our nation‚Äôs food supply and those we trade with. Despite this, the upcoming continuing resolution fails to include the essential economic reforms and natural disaster coverage many farmers need to survive the recent wave of natural disasters and worldwide flat crop prices. 

Without immediate relief, farmers may not be able to produce in 2025, nor even get banks to finance them. Many face the auction block sooner than many Americans would realize. Congress must prioritize these needs and deliver the support that will help agriculture stay afloat and continue to drive our economy forward and keep our food supply secure. We can do a lot in the next two years to eliminate the useless regulations that drive up costs to farmers and related businesses. With President Trumps help, and that of new Trade Representative Greer, we can crackdown on unfair foreign dumping of heavily subsidized, underpriced, inferior products that undercut ours. We must do the immediate relief we can now, to give us the time to fix those longer term trade issues.

Name: Whitehouse, Sheldon
text: Maybe Think About It This Way: ¬†Is our problem that the far right has declared war on normal America, and set up a war machine to accomplish that goal, and Democrats aren‚Äôt even set up to detect and defend against that war machine?

Name: Whitehouse, Sheldon
text: Thought experiment: What if Churchill had been a Democrat in those darkest hours? Surely Churchill-the-Democrat would have gone out and commiserated with Londoners whose homes had been blown up by buzz bombs. As he did.

Name: Whitehouse, Sheldon
text: Surely Churchill-the-Democrat would have pushed Parliament for an infrastructure program to help Londoners rebuild after the bombing. For sure we‚Äôd do that.

Name: Whitehouse, Sheldon
text: But would Churchill-the-Democrat have built a command center deep under the streets of London? (Hint: Democrats don‚Äôt have one against the far-right war machine.)

Name: Whitehouse, Sheldon
text: Would there have been radar along the English coast detecting and identifying incoming attacks? (Hint: we don‚Äôt have that; we usually wait until attacks by the far-right war machine land, and then complain about them. We count on reporters to do the work.)

Name: Whitehouse, Sheldon
text: Would there be Spitfires in the sky, bravely fighting to win the Battle of Britain, with so many ultimately owing so much to so few? (Hint: ¬†nowhere in our Democratic ecosystem is there any place devoted to counterattacking the far-right war machine, by real-time exposing and discrediting it.)

Name: Whitehouse, Sheldon
text: Would the Ruhr Valley have been lit up at night by Mosquito bombing raids to disrupt the weapons manufacture supplying the attacks on England? (Hint: ¬†Democrats don‚Äôt even have institutional awareness of where/how far-right smears, self-serving theories, and propaganda are produced and beta-tested ‚Äî let alone exposing them.)

Name: Collins, Mike
text:
On #ThisDayInHistory in 1773, the Boston Tea Party occurred when a group of Massachusetts colonists disguised as Mohawk Indians boarded three ships in Boston Harbor and dumped 342 chests of tea into the water.

The Boston Tea Party was a protest against the British Parliament's Tea Act, which aimed to save the struggling East India Company by reducing its tax on tea and granting it a monopoly on the American tea trade. Although the Tea Act didn‚Äôt raise the price of tea, it allowed the company to undercut smuggled Dutch tea, which angered many colonists who saw it as another form of British control and "taxation without representation."

When the governor refused to allow the tea to be sent back to Britain, Samuel Adams organized the raid with the Sons of Liberty. The destruction of tea, valued at nearly $2 million today, prompted the British to pass the Coercive Acts (Intolerable Acts), which closed Boston's ports and imposed harsher British rule in Massachusetts. This led to the formation of the First Continental Congress, uniting the colonies in opposition to Britain.

text:
Today, I made demands on Secretary Mayorkas of the Department of Homeland Security (DHS), for immediate federal action in response to the increasing reports of unidentified drones near critical infrastructure in southeastern Pennsylvania. Although federal administration officials have thus far indicated that there is no immediate threat, these drones present serious security concerns that need to be addressed immediately.

In addition to my call for action, I am asking for an immediate vote on H.R. 4333, of which I am a co-sponsor, the Safeguarding the Homeland from the Threats Posed by Unmanned Aircraft Systems Act. This bipartisan bill aims to enhance the federal government‚Äôs ability to protect Americans from the risks associated with unmanned aircraft systems (UAS). This crucial legislation will reauthorize existing authorities and create new opportunities for federal agencies to coordinate counter-drone measures with state and local governments.

I remain committed to uncovering the facts, holding our agencies accountable, and ensuring our communities receive the action and answers they deserve. Protecting the safety and security of our families and critical infrastructure will always be my top priority.

Name: Collins, Mike
text:
On #ThisDayInHistory in 1903, near Kitty Hawk, North Carolina, Orville and Wilbur Wright made history with the first successful flight of a self-propelled, heavier-than-air aircraft. 

Orville piloted their gasoline-powered biplane, which flew for 12 seconds and covered 120 feet. The brothers made a total of four flights that day, with Orville and Wilbur alternately piloting the aircraft. The final flight, however, ended in a dramatic mishap. As the brothers were discussing the flight, a strong gust of wind flipped the Wright Flyer several times, causing severe damage. The aircraft was beyond repair, and it was crated and transported back to Dayton, never to fly again.

Over the following years, the Wright brothers continued to refine their aircraft. Their planes could perform complex maneuvers and stay aloft for 39 minutes. They made their first public flights in France and the U.S. Army purchased a plane. The brothers founded the Wright Company to build and market their aircraft. The Wright brothers‚Äô historic 1903 aircraft is now displayed at the National Air and Space Museum in Washington, D.C.

Name: Whitehouse, Sheldon
text: The story begins years ago, after the god-awful Citizens United decision came down from the Supreme Court‚Äôs FedSoc cohort.

Name: Whitehouse, Sheldon
text: Republicans were ready, and launched dozens of 501c4 organizations to take advantage of the new unlimited spending (much of it even allowed to be secret). The IRS oversees 501c4s, and noticed the sudden flood of applications and activity.

Name: Whitehouse, Sheldon
text: 501c4s are restricted in their political activity, so there were lots of compliance questions to be asked.

Name: Whitehouse, Sheldon
text: The IRS set up a review process for plainly political 501c4s, most of which were right-wing (but not all) for the obvious reason that most of the immediate activity was¬†political.

Name: Whitehouse, Sheldon
text: ‚ÄúFaux outrage‚Äù is a standard technique of the far right, and the faux outrage machine was dialed up to full blast: IRS commissioner threatened with impeachment; top staffer referred to DOJ for criminal investigation.

Name: Whitehouse, Sheldon
text: (Nothing makes a powerful creepy right-wing billionaire, who‚Äôs out to do nasty mischief in our political system, happier than the narrative that they are poor, put-upon victims ‚Äî it would take a psychoanalyst to sort out why, but it‚Äôs observable. They love to feel like victims.)

Name: Whitehouse, Sheldon
text: The IRS was barraged with complaints about political victimization.

Name: Whitehouse, Sheldon
text: In the face of that barrage, the Obama administration turned tail; even bought into the right-wing narrative. The message to the IRS was plain: do your job in this area at your peril.

Name: Whitehouse, Sheldon
text: The message was received: review of 501c4s was abandoned, opening up our political spending Wild West.

Name: Whitehouse, Sheldon
text: A problem for 501c4 donors was that they could only get half their money spent on political ads, so it was expensive for political donors (sweet for the 501c4s, though). Likely, there was a lot of cheating, but with the IRS cowed from investigation, who‚Äôd check?

Name: Whitehouse, Sheldon
text: Tricks emerged, like cycling donations through connected 501c4s: 50% on politics by Group A, remainder to Group B to spend 50% on politics, remainder to Group C to spend 50% on politics, etc. Put a few lawyers in a room, and donor political efficiency can get over 90%.

Name: Whitehouse, Sheldon
text: Even at 50%, it was still a sweet deal, as the political influence the creepy billionaires deployed bought benefits ten-fold or even hundred-fold the money spent. But the ROI goes up if you can get more political spending for your donor dollar.

Name: Whitehouse, Sheldon
text: The state of the art in political influence then moved to twinned 501c4s and 501c3s.¬† 501c3s aren‚Äôt supposed to do any politics, but 501c3 donors get tax deductions and more secrecy for dark-money operations, so it‚Äôs tempting. Particularly with no cops.

Name: Whitehouse, Sheldon
text: Twinned 501c3/501c4s share offices, staff, donors, board members ‚Äî you could ‚Äúpierce the corporate veil‚Äù between them with a banana. But with no investigation and no enforcement, it‚Äôs free to cheat in the dark-money Wild West.

Name: Whitehouse, Sheldon
text: From the original cowardice of the Obama administration, through the long tail of learned cowardice and deliberate inactivity at the IRS, the result has been massive corruption of our politics using trickery that has never had to pass inspection.

Name: Whitehouse, Sheldon
text: With the Trumpsters coming to town, you can pretty much bet that this enforcement no-fly zone is going to get worse, and dark-money trickery will get worse accordingly. Watch your wallets, because dark-money influence is there to make them richer, not you.

Name: Whitehouse, Sheldon
text: So that‚Äôs the ‚Äúrest of the story‚Äù (thanks, Paul Harvey) on how creepy billionaires get to use your tax dollars to fund their highly political Project 2025 and other nasty mischief.

Hamas doesn‚Äôt fight fair. They hide behind civilians, building tunnels under hospitals, schools, and homes, knowing full well Israel‚Äôs rules of engagement will hold them back.

John Spencer (@SpencerGuard), Chair of Urban Warfare Studies at West Point, breaks it down: when armies can‚Äôt use precision strikes, wars become longer, bloodier, and deadlier. Just look at Stalingrad, where a single building became a months-long fight. Gaza is no different‚Äîthis is what happens when terrorists exploit humanity‚Äôs moral restraint.

John joined me to cut through the myths about urban combat and explain the realities unfolding in Ukraine, Syria, and Gaza. We also look ahead: what would a Chinese invasion of Taiwan look like? How do we combat cartels on our southern border? These are the hard questions we have to confront if we want to win wars and protect civilians.

Name: Brownley, Julia
text: Frances Perkins made history as the first woman in a presidential cabinet, but her legacy extends far beyond breaking the glass ceiling. Serving as Secretary of Labor from 1933 to 1945, Perkins was the leading architect behind the New Deal and is widely credited with creating the modern middle class and playing a critical role in the passage of the Social Security Act in 1935.

Name: Brownley, Julia
text: Yesterday, President Biden formally designated the Frances Perkins Homestead as a national monument, a significant step in honoring her life and legacy. The boundaries of this new national monument will encompass the 57 acres of the Frances Perkins Homestead National Historic Landmark in Newcastle, Maine. This is the place where Perkins spent her childhood summers, and she frequently returned to throughout her groundbreaking and monumental career in public service.

Name: Brownley, Julia
text: With so few of our national park sites designated to honoring women, it is important that we continue to celebrate the immeasurable contributions of trailblazers like Perkins. Perkins‚Äô work is deserving of a permanent place in the National Park Service, and I am thrilled that President Biden is amplifying the stories of women who have shaped American history.
